{{Infobox symptom | Image = | Caption = Wong-Baker Faces, Pediatric Pain Scale | Field = [[Pediatrics]], [[Anesthesia]], [[Neonatal medicine]], [[Palliative medicine]] | ICD10 = {{ICD10|R|52}} | ICD9 = {{ICD9|338}} | MedlinePlus = 002164 | DiseasesDB = 9503 | MeshID = D010146 }} '''Pain management in children''' is the assessment and treatment of [[pain]] in [[infant]]s and [[child]]ren.<ref name=":0">{{cite journal | vauthors = Verghese ST, Hannallah RS | title = Acute pain management in children | journal = Journal of Pain Research | volume = 3 | pages = 105–23 | date = July 2010 | pmid = 21197314 | pmc = 3004641 }}</ref>
==Acute pain== Usually, [[acute pain]] has an obvious cause and is expected to last for a few days or weeks. It is usually managed with medication and non-pharmacological treatment to provide comfort.{{sfn|Twycross|page=140}} Acute pain is an indication for needed assessment, treatment and prevention. While a child is experiencing pain, physiological consequences can jeopardize healing and recovery. Unrelieved pain can cause [[alkalosis]] and [[hypoxemia]] that result from rapid, shallow breathing. This shallow breathing can lead to the accumulation of fluid in the lungs, taking away the ability to cough. Pain can cause an increase in blood pressure and heart rate, putting stress on the heart. Pain also increases the release of anti-inflammatory [[steroid]]s that reduce the ability to fight infection, increase the metabolic rate and affect healing. Another harmful outcome of acute pain is an increase in [[Sympathetic nervous system|sympathetic]] effects such as the inability to urinate. Pain can also slow the gastrointestinal system.
Inadequate pain management in children can lead to psycho-social consequences, including lack of interest in food, apathy, sleep problems, anxiety, avoidance of discussions about health, fear, hopelessness and powerlessness. Other consequences include extended hospital stays, high re-admission rates and longer recovery.{{sfn|Twycross | page = 3}}
Examples of harmful consequences of unrelieved pain include:{{sfn|Twycross|page =1}} *Infants who have had more than average [[Neonatal heel prick|heel pricks]] can have poor cognitive and motor function; *Associations of needles with distress may make later medical treatments more difficult; *Children who have experienced invasive procedures often develop [[Posttraumatic stress disorder|post-traumatic stress]]; *Boys circumcised without anesthesia were found to have greater distress than uncircumcised boys;{{sfn|twycross|page= 3}} *Severe pain as a child is associated with higher reports of pain in adults.{{sfn|Twycross | page =2}}
==Neuropathic pain== [[Peripheral neuropathy|Neuropathic pain]] is associated with nerve injuries or abnormal sensitivities to touch or contact. Though neuropathic pain is relatively uncommon in children compared to adults, greater awareness of these conditions is on the rise.<ref name=":4">{{cite journal | vauthors = Walco GA, Dworkin RH, Krane EJ, LeBel AA, Treede RD | title = Neuropathic pain in children: Special considerations | journal = Mayo Clinic Proceedings | volume = 85 | issue = 3 Suppl | pages = S33–41 | date = March 2010 | pmid = 20194147 | pmc = 2844006 | doi = 10.4065/mcp.2009.0647 }}</ref> Some causes may include past surgeries and amputations,<ref name=":5">{{Cite news|url=https://www.stjude.org/treatment/patient-resources/caregiver-resources/patient-family-education-sheets/rehabilitation/neuropathic-pain.html|title=Neuropathic pain|access-date=2018-11-02|language=en-US}}</ref> "autoimmune and degenerative neuropathies",<ref name=":4" /> and injury to the spinal cord.<ref name=":4" />
Symptoms may include a tingling, shooting, prickling or burning sensation. The pain can be intermittent or continual and is often exacerbates in the evenings.<ref name=":5" /><ref name=":6">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hauer J, Houtrow AJ | title = Pain Assessment and Treatment in Children With Significant Impairment of the Central Nervous System | journal = Pediatrics | volume = 139 | issue = 6 | pages = e20171002 | date = June 2017 | pmid = 28562301 | doi = 10.1542/peds.2017-1002 | url = http://pediatrics.aappublications.org/content/139/6/e20171002 }}</ref>
Neuropathic pain can be peripheral or central. Peripheral neuropathic pain refers to disturbance in the function of peripheral nerves while central neuropathic pain refers to nerves in the central nervous system.
Though not FDA-approved to address pain in children, anticonvulsants such as gabapentin and pregabalin have been used in severe neuropathic impairment (SNI).<ref name=":6" /> Other options are serotonin-norepinephrine reuptake inhibitors (SNRIs). Despite limited studies in children (limited to those with depression), SNRIs such as Venlafaxine have been shown to be effective.<ref name=":6" />
==Cancer pain== Cancer pain in children may be caused by the cancer itself or the side effects of treatment. Tumors can cause pain in two different ways, either by the physical pressure it places on organs or by occluding normal bodily functions. Treatment such as surgery and injections can also lead to significant pain for the patient. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cancer.ca/en/cancer-information/cancer-type/childhood-cancer-information/pain-in-children/?region=on#|title=Pain in children - Canadian Cancer Society|website=www.cancer.ca|language=en|access-date=2018-11-19}}</ref> If untreated, the pain can suppress the immune, interfere with sleep, and increase the chance of depression. Many different health care professionals will manage the child's pain and are referred to as the patient's [[palliative care]] team, these include oncologists, anesthesiologists, neurologists, surgeons, psychiatrists, and pharmacists. Hospitals may also hire individuals who specialize in music or art therapy, these therapies include acupuncture, biofeedback, massage therapy, and hypnosis. <ref name=":7">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cancer.gov/publications/patient-education/guide-for-parents|title=Children with Cancer: A Guide for Parents|website=National Cancer Institute|language=en|access-date=2018-11-19|date=2015-09-09}}</ref>
Treatment of the cancer pain is tailored to the child based on age, treatment, and side effects. The goal is to achieve sufficient background control of pain and minimize any acute exacerbation of severe pain. Often times medications such as non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs), acetaminophen, or opiates are used to manage the pain. Additionally, non-pharmacological can also be used to manage the child's pain, this includes distracting the child, massages, acupuncture, heat/cold therapy, exercise, and quality sleep. <ref name=":7" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Friedrichsdorf|first=Stefan J|last2=Postier|first2=Andrea|date=2014-03-07|title=Management of breakthrough pain in children with cancer|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3953108/|journal=Journal of Pain Research|volume=7|pages=117–123|doi=10.2147/JPR.S58862|issn=1178-7090|pmc=3953108|pmid=24639603}}</ref>
==Chronic pain== Chronic pain in children is unresolved pain that affects [[activities of daily living]] and may result in a significant amount of missed school days. Chronic pain is present for long periods of time and is characterized as mild to severe.{{mcn|date=October 2018}} Chronic pain has also been described as the pain experienced when the child reports a headache, abdominal pain, back pain, generalized pain or combination of these.{{mcn|date=October 2018}} Chronic pain can develop from disease or injury and can occur simultaneously with acute pain. Children who experience chronic pain can have psychological effects. Caring for a child in pain may cause distress to the caregiver, may cause costs due to healthcare or lost wages from time off work, and may stop caregivers from leaving the house.
==Assessment== {{further|Pain assessment}} [[File:Children's pain scale.JPG|thumb|upright=1.8 | Example pain assessment chart]]
Assessment of pain in children depends on the cooperation and developmental stage of the child. Some children cannot assist in their assessment because they have not matured enough cognitively, emotionally, or physically.{{sfn|Henry|page=43}} The following sections list signs of distress and possible pain in children by age group:
===Younger infants=== {{further|Infant crying}} * Inability to distinguish the stimulus from the pain * Ability to exhibit a reflexive response to pain * Expressions of pain **Tightly closed eyes{{mcn|date=October 2018}} **Open mouth resembling a square rather than an oval or circle **Eyebrows lowered and tightly drawn together * Rigid body * Thrashing * Loud crying{{sfn | Henry | page = 43}} * Increase in heart rate, even while sleeping
===Older infants=== * Deliberate withdrawal from pain and possible guarding * Loud crying * Painful facial expressions{{sfn | Henry | page = 43}}
===Toddlers=== Toddlers show signs of distress and possible pain by: * Expressing pain verbally * Thrashing extremities * Crying loudly * Screaming * Being uncooperative * [[Palpation|Palpating]] (examining with the hands) a source of pain * Anticipating a pain-inducing procedure or event * Requesting to be comforted * Clinging to a significant person, possibly one perceived as protective{{sfn | Henry | page = 43}}
===School-age children=== School-age children show signs of distress and possible pain by: * Anticipating the pain but less intensively, (understands concepts of time, i.e., imminent vs future pain) * Stalling, trying to talk out of the situation where pain is anticipated * Having muscular rigidity{{sfn|Henry|page = 43}}
===Adolescent=== Adolescents show signs of distress and possible pain: * With muscle tension, but with control * With verbal expressions and descriptions{{sfn | Henry | page = 43}}
===Quantitative pain assessment=== Although pain is subjective and can occur in a continuous spectrum of intensities, there are assessment tools that compare pain levels over time. This kind of assessment incorporates pain scales and requires a high enough developmental level for the child to respond to questions.{{sfn | Henry | page=43}} A verbal response is not always necessary to quantify pain.
===Pain scales=== A [[pain scale]] measures a patient's pain intensity and other features. Pain scales can be based on observational (behavioral) or physiological data, as well as self-report. Self-report is considered primary and should be obtained if possible. Pain measurements help determine the severity, type, and duration of pain. They are also used in diagnosis, to determine a treatment plan, and to evaluate the effectiveness of treatment. Pain scales are available for neonates, infants, children, adolescents, adults, seniors, and persons with impaired communication. Pain assessments are often regarded as "the 5th [[vital sign]]".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.npcnow.org/system/files/research/download/Pain-Current-Understanding-of-Assessment-Management-and-Treatments.pdf |title=Pain: current understanding of assessment, management and treatments|date=December 2001 |publisher=Joint Commission on Accreditation of Healthcare Organizations andnthe National Pharmaceutical Council, Inc.|access-date=2018-01-25}} {{outdated-inline|date=October 2018}}</ref>
{| class="wikitable" border="1" |+ Examples of pain scales |- ! ! Self-report ! Observational ! Physiological |- | Infant | — | Premature Infant Pain Profile; Neonatal/Infant Pain Scale | — |- | Child | [[Wong-Baker Faces Pain Rating Scale]] – Revised;<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Drendel AL, Kelly BT, Ali S | title = Pain assessment for children: overcoming challenges and optimizing care | journal = Pediatric Emergency Care | volume = 27 | issue = 8 | pages = 773–81 | date = August 2011 | pmid = 21822093 | doi = 10.1097/PEC.0b013e31822877f7 }}</ref> Coloured Analogue Scale<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Stinson JN, Kavanagh T, Yamada J, Gill N, Stevens B | title = Systematic review of the psychometric properties, interpretability and feasibility of self-report pain intensity measures for use in clinical trials in children and adolescents | journal = Pain | volume = 125 | issue = 1–2 | pages = 143–57 | date = November 2006 | pmid = 16777328 | doi = 10.1016/j.pain.2006.05.006 }}</ref> | [[FLACC scale|FLACC]] (Face Legs Arms Cry Consolability Scale); CHEOPS (Children's Hospital of Eastern Ontario Pain Scale)<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = von Baeyer CL, Spagrud LJ | title = Systematic review of observational (behavioral) measures of pain for children and adolescents aged 3 to 18 years | journal = Pain | volume = 127 | issue = 1–2 | pages = 140–50 | date = January 2007 | pmid = 16996689 | doi = 10.1016/j.pain.2006.08.014 }}</ref> | Comfort |- | Adolescent | [[Visual Analog Scale]] (VAS); Verbal Numerical Rating Scale (VNRS); Verbal Descriptor Scale (VDS); [[Brief Pain Inventory]] | — | — |}
==Causes== The causes of pain in children are similar to the causes in adults.
Pain can be experienced in many ways and depends on the following factors in each child: * Prior painful episodes or treatments * Age and [[Human development (biology)|developmental stage]] * Disease or type of trauma * Personality * Culture * Socioeconomic status * Presence of family members and family dynamics.{{sfn|Henry|page = 43}}
==During treatment== [[File:US Navy 060822-N-2832L-128 Navy Lt. Rachel Oden, of Casa Grande, Ariz., a physical therapist plays with a young girl during her first day of physical therapy for her neuromuscular control deficits.jpg|thumb|A physical therapist uses play as part of a child's treatment plan]] Clinicians responsible for a child monitor the child frequently in tertiary care centers (hospitals). Pharmacological and non-pharmacological treatments are used to manage the pain. Parents or caregivers are also requested to provide their own pain assessments. At the beginning of pharmacological treatment, clinicians monitor the child for [[Adverse effect|adverse reactions]] to the medications. The levels of some medications are monitored to ensure that the child is not over-medicated and does not receive toxic levels of any drug. The levels also indicate whether there would be enough drug in the blood to be effective in managing the pain. Medications are metabolized differently between children of the same age. Factors that influence the levels of medications controlling pain include the height, weight, and body surface of the child, as well as any other illnesses.{{sfn|Henry|page=43}} Some medications may have a [[paradoxical effect]] in children, which is an effect that is the opposite of the expected effect. Clinicians monitor for this and any other reactions to medication.<ref name="Moon2013">{{cite journal | vauthors = Moon YE | title = Paradoxical reaction to midazolam in children | journal = Korean Journal of Anesthesiology | volume = 65 | issue = 1 | pages = 2–3 | date = July 2013 | pmid = 23904931 | pmc = 3726842 | doi = 10.4097/kjae.2013.65.1.2 }}</ref><ref name="MancusoTanzi2004">{{cite journal | vauthors = Mancuso CE, Tanzi MG, Gabay M | title = Paradoxical reactions to benzodiazepines: literature review and treatment options | journal = Pharmacotherapy | volume = 24 | issue = 9 | pages = 1177–85 | date = September 2004 | pmid = 15460178 }} {{outdated-inline|date=October 2018}}</ref>
== After treatment == Post-procedural treatment in children is primarily prescription opioids. Morphine is effective and relatively safe, and is often used with moderate to severe pain.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Friedrichsdorf SJ, Kang TI | title = The management of pain in children with life-limiting illnesses | journal = Pediatric Clinics of North America | volume = 54 | issue = 5 | pages = 645–72, x | date = October 2007 | pmid = 17933616 | doi = 10.1016/j.pcl.2007.07.007 | url = https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0031395507001162 }}</ref> Codeine and tramadol should be avoided especially in children younger than 12 years old since metabolism varies due to genetic differences between individuals.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ciszkowski C, Madadi P, Phillips MS, Lauwers AE, Koren G | title = Codeine, ultrarapid-metabolism genotype, and postoperative death | language = EN | journal = The New England Journal of Medicine | volume = 361 | issue = 8 | pages = 827–8 | date = August 2009 | pmid = 19692698 | doi = 10.1056/nejmc0904266 }}</ref> However, other interventions include medications classified as non-opioid analgesics, which are useful in post surgical treatment.<ref name="White S5">{{cite journal | vauthors = White PF | title = The changing role of non-opioid analgesic techniques in the management of postoperative pain | journal = Anesthesia and Analgesia | volume = 101 | issue = 5 Suppl | pages = S5–22 | date = November 2005 | pmid = 16334489 }} {{outdated-inline|date=October 2018}}</ref> For example, acetaminophen or ibuprofen can be used as a non-opioid analgesics. Unlike acetaminophen, ibuprofen has anti-inflammatory property which can be useful for pain in inflammatory conditions. Aspirin is not used in pediatric population due to its association with Reye's syndrome.
==Atraumatic measures== Because children process information differently from adults, treatment centers for children often use atraumatic measures to reduce anxiety and stress. Examples include: * Allowing the parent or caregiver to be present for painful procedures * Using a treatment room for painful procedures to ensure that the child's room is a place where little pain can be expected * Establishing other "pain-free zones" where no medical procedures are allowed, such as a playroom * Offering choices to the child to give them some control over the procedures * Modelling procedures with dolls and toys * Using age-appropriate anatomical terms and other vocabulary.{{sfn|Henry|page=43}}
==Non-pharmacological pain management== Depending on the source of pain, there are many non-pharmacological options to be considered. Also, depending on the age of the child, different approaches may be more suitable.
Non-pharmacological methods to manage discomfort during immunizations include putting sugar on a [[pacifier]]<!--wikilinked as this term is not well known in Australia-->, comforting the child during and after the injection, chest-to-chest hugging, and letting the child choose the injection site.<ref name="healthychildren.org">{{cite web|url=https://www.healthychildren.org/English/safety-prevention/immunizations/Pages/Managing-Your-Childs-Pain-While-Getting-a-Shot.aspx|title=Managing Your Child's Pain While Getting a Shot|website=HealthyChildren.org|access-date=20 August 2017}}</ref> Other non-pharmacological treatments that have been found to be effective include:
* Carefully explaining a procedure with pictures or other visual aids * Allowing the child to ask questions of medical staff * Touring the place where the procedures will occur * Allowing small children to play with dolls or other toys with a clinician to understand the procedure * Allowing older children to watch a video that explains the procedure * Providing distraction with songs, stories, toys, color, videos, TV, or music * Using relaxation techniques such as deep breathing or massage <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chambers|first=Christine|date=2009|title=Psychological interventions for reducing pain and distress during routine childhood immunizations: A systematic review|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0149291809002628|journal=Clinical Therapeutics|volume=31|pages=S77–S103|via=|pmid=19781437|doi=10.1016/j.clinthera.2009.07.023}}</ref>
Non-pharmacological treatment for pain associated with [[venipuncture]] in children includes [[hypnosis]] and distraction. These treatments reduced self-reported pain and when combined with [[Cognitive behavioral therapy|cognitive-behavioural therapy]] (CBT) the reduction of pain was even greater. Other interventions have not been found to be effective and these are suggestion, blowing out air, and distraction with parent coaching did not differ from control for pain and distress.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Robertson J | title = Review: distraction, hypnosis, and combined cognitive-behavioural interventions reduce needle related pain and distress in children and adolescents | journal = Evidence-Based Nursing | volume = 10 | issue = 3 | pages = 75 | date = July 2007 | pmid = 17596380 | doi = 10.1136/ebn.10.3.75 }}</ref>
[[Breastfeeding]] during painful procedures has been found to be more effective in controlling pain than [[placebo]] or positioning. Breastmilk or 'sugar' water has a similar effect, though studies in preterm infants have yet to be done.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Shah PS, Herbozo C, Aliwalas LL, Shah VS | title = Breastfeeding or breast milk for procedural pain in neonates | journal = The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews | volume = 12 | pages = CD004950 | date = December 2012 | pmid = 23235618 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD004950.pub3 }}</ref> Skin-to-skin care ([[kangaroo care]]) is thought be effective for pain control during painful procedures.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Johnston C, Campbell-Yeo M, Disher T, Benoit B, Fernandes A, Streiner D, Inglis D, Zee R | title = Skin-to-skin care for procedural pain in neonates | journal = The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews | volume = 2 | pages = CD008435 | date = February 2017 | pmid = 28205208 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD008435.pub3 }}</ref>
For children and adolescents who experience chronic pain- behavioral treatment, relaxation training, cognitive behavioral therapy (CBT) and acupuncture have been proven to be effective for some patients.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mu|first=Pei-Fan|date=2009|title=The effectiveness of non-pharmacological pain management in relieving chronic pain for children and adolescents.|url=|journal=JBI Library of Systematic Reviews|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>
==Pharmacotherapy== {{See|Analgesic adjuvant}} Acute pain, chronic pain, neuropathic pain and recurrent pain in children is most often managed with medication. Most of these medications are [[analgesic]]s. These include [[acetaminophen]], [[NSAIDs]], [[local anesthetic]]s, [[opioid]]s, and medications for neuropathic pain. The most effective approach to pain management in children is to provide pain control around the clock instead of providing pain relief as needed. Regional anesthesia is also effective and recommended whenever possible. It is important to use caution when administering opioids to neonates and young infants. There is a higher risk for apnea and hypoventilation in this population, due to their decreased breathing response.<ref name=":0" />
===Chronic pain treatment=== Chronic pain is treated with a variety of medications and non-pharmacological interventions. The World Health Organization recommends using a two step treatment approach based on the level of pain in children. The first step explains mild pain treatment, while the second step considers moderate to severe pain. Opioids, such as morphine, is an example of a drug of choice for moderate-severe pain in children with medical illnesses.<ref>World Health Organization. (2012). Pharmacological treatment of persistent pain in children with medical illnesses. Retrieved from http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/44540/9789241548120_Guidelines.pdf?sequence=1</ref> Some side effects of opioid use can include cognition deficits, dependence, altered mood, and disturbances of endocrine development.
Non-pharmacological treatment for children to help relieve periodic pain includes counseling and [[behavior modification]] therapy.{{mcn|date=October 2018}}The American Association of Pediatrics states that psychological interventions, such as relaxation and cognitive strategies, have strong evidence for pain management.<ref>American Pain Society. (2012). Assessment and Management of Children with Chronic Pain [Position statement]. Retrieved from http://americanpainsociety.org/uploads/get-involved/pediatric-chronic-pain-statement.pdf</ref>
===Acute pain treatment=== The approach to acute pain should take into account the severity of the pain. Non-opioid analgesics, such as [[acetaminophen]] and [[Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug|NSAIDs]], can be used alone to treat mild pain.<ref name=":0" /> For moderate to severe pain, it is optimal to use a combination of multiple agents, including opioid and non-opioid agents.<ref name=":0" />
===== Postoperative pain ===== A panel, including the American Pain Society and American Society of Regional Anesthesia and Pain Medicine, recommends multimodal analgesia, which they define as a combination of pharmacological agents and non-pharmacological techniques to treat postoperative pain.<ref name=":1">{{cite journal | vauthors = Chou R, Gordon DB, de Leon-Casasola OA, Rosenberg JM, Bickler S, Brennan T, Carter T, Cassidy CL, Chittenden EH, Degenhardt E, Griffith S, Manworren R, McCarberg B, Montgomery R, Murphy J, Perkal MF, Suresh S, Sluka K, Strassels S, Thirlby R, Viscusi E, Walco GA, Warner L, Weisman SJ, Wu CL | title = Management of Postoperative Pain: A Clinical Practice Guideline From the American Pain Society, the American Society of Regional Anesthesia and Pain Medicine, and the American Society of Anesthesiologists' Committee on Regional Anesthesia, Executive Committee, and Administrative Council | language = English | journal = The Journal of Pain | volume = 17 | issue = 2 | pages = 131–57 | date = February 2016 | pmid = 26827847 | doi = 10.1016/j.jpain.2015.12.008 }}</ref> A significant benefit of this technique is that non-opioid analgesics used in combination with opioids can decrease the amount of opioids required and reduce the risk of opioid-related side effects.<ref name=":0" /> Medications can be delivered as needed or around-the-clock depending on the patient’s needs. For children, intravenous patient-controlled analgesia (IV-PCA) an be used when parenteral administration is preferred.<ref name=":1" /> IV-PCA allows for consistent opioid levels, which can be a better alternative to scheduled intramuscular injections.<ref name=":0" /> In addition, studies have shown that children as young as 6 years old can use the IV-PCA correctly.<ref name=":1" />
===== Dental pain ===== For projected moderate to severe pain, analgesics can be used on a regular schedule for the first 36 to 48 hours after a dental procedure.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=http://www.aapd.org/policies/|title=Policy on Acute Pediatric Dental Pain Management |date=2017|website=American Academy of Pediatric Dentistry |access-date=29 October 2018}}</ref> NSAIDs are preferred over other analgesics to treat acute mild to moderate postoperative pain, due to the inflammatory component of dental pain.<ref name=":2" /><ref name=":3">{{cite journal | vauthors = Becker DE | title = Pain management: Part 1: Managing acute and postoperative dental pain | journal = Anesthesia Progress | volume = 57 | issue = 2 | pages = 67–78; quiz 79–80 | date = 2010 | pmid = 20553137 | pmc = 2886920 | doi = 10.2344/0003-3006-57.2.67 }}</ref> Alternating between the NSAIDs and acetaminophen in combination is another option.<ref name=":2" /> In addition, these two agents are considered equivalent or better than opioids for managing musculoskeletal pain, which includes dental pain.<ref name=":3" />
===Cancer pain treatment=== Cancer pain is managed differently in children. Typically, medical history, physical examinations, age and overall health of the child are evaluated. The type of cancer may influence decisions about pain management. The extent of the cancer, and the tolerance of the child to specific medications, procedures or therapies are also taken into account, as well as the preferences of the parent or caregiver.{{mcn|date=October 2018}} Medications used to treat cancer pain include non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cooper|first=Tess E|last2=Heathcote|first2=Lauren C|last3=Anderson|first3=Brian|last4=Grégoire|first4=Marie-Claude|last5=Ljungman|first5=Gustaf|last6=Eccleston|first6=Christopher|date=2017-07-24|title=Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) for cancer-related pain in children and adolescents|url=https://www.cochrane.org/CD012563/SYMPT_nsaids-cancer-related-pain-children-and-adolescents|journal=Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|volume=7|pages=CD012563|language=en|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD012563.pub2|pmid=28737843|issn=1465-1858}}</ref> and opioids.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wiffen|first=Philip J|last2=Cooper|first2=Tess E|last3=Anderson|first3=Anna-Karenia|last4=Gray|first4=Andrew L|last5=Grégoire|first5=Marie-Claude|last6=Ljungman|first6=Gustaf|last7=Zernikow|first7=Boris|date=2017-07-19|title=Opioids for cancer-related pain in children and adolescents|journal=Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|volume=7|pages=CD012564|doi=10.1002/14651858.cd012564.pub2|pmid=28722116|issn=1465-1858}}</ref>
===== Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) =====
* Used as treatment for pain and anti-inflammatory * Can be administered as oral tablet or liquid * Recommended to use lowest dose and shortest duration possible to control pain * Not approved for infants < 3 months old * General adverse effects for NSAIDs: ** Renal impairment ** Hepatic impairment ** Gastrointestinal issues (Nausea, diarrhea, constipation, flatulence) **[[Indigestion|Dyspepsia]] ** Rash ** Dizziness ** Abdominal pain * Contraindicated for: **[[Hypersensitivity|Hypersensitivity reactions]] ** Cardiac impairment **[[Reye syndrome|Reye's syndrome]] ** Coagulation defects * Ibuprofen 5–10&nbsp;mg/kg every 6–8 hours (Max dose 1200&nbsp;mg/day)
===== Opioids =====
* Doses based on child's body weight * Can be administered as oral, parenteral, buccal, transdermal, nasal or rectal formulations * Recommended to start at low dose and titrate up to effect * General adverse effects for opioids: ** Constipation ** Hives ** Nausea ** Vomiting ** Pruritus ** Respiratory depression
== Opioids== The frequency of prescribing for these pain medications has more than doubled from 1990 to 2010 with 20-50% of adolescents who complain of headache, back pain, or joint pain receiving a prescribed opioid.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = DeVries A, Koch T, Wall E, Getchius T, Chi W, Rosenberg A | title = Opioid use among adolescent patients treated for headache | journal = The Journal of Adolescent Health | volume = 55 | issue = 1 | pages = 128–33 | date = July 2014 | pmid = 24581795 | doi = 10.1016/j.jadohealth.2013.12.014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Mazer-Amirshahi M, Mullins PM, Rasooly IR, van den Anker J, Pines JM | title = Trends in prescription opioid use in pediatric emergency department patients | journal = Pediatric Emergency Care | volume = 30 | issue = 4 | pages = 230–5 | date = April 2014 | pmid = 24651218 | doi = 10.1097/pec.0000000000000102 }}</ref>
Before an adolescent or young adult is prescribed opioids, they should be screened for risk factors for opioid drug abuse. Prescription drug monitoring programs (PDMs) are now available in 37 states and 11 states have programs in development.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Peck KR, Ehrentraut JH, Anghelescu DL | title = Risk factors for opioid misuse in adolescents and young adults with focus on oncology setting | journal = Journal of Opioid Management | volume = 12 | issue = 3 | pages = 205–16 | date = 2016-05-01 | pmid = 27435441 | doi = 10.5055/jom.2016.0333 }}</ref>
===Adverse effects=== The use of opioids can result in a number of complications in children, including respiratory depression and risk for unintended overdose and opioid misuse later in life. These risks can be reduced by the use of [[Nsaids|NSAIDs]] (e.g. ibuprofen) and [[paracetamol]]. Using NSAIDs and paracetamol can be opioid-sparing, leading to less opioid use in situations such as peri-operative pain management.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Wong I, St John-Green C, Walker SM | title = Opioid-sparing effects of perioperative paracetamol and nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) in children | journal = Paediatric Anaesthesia | volume = 23 | issue = 6 | pages = 475–95 | date = June 2013 | pmid = 23570544 | pmc = 4272569 | doi = 10.1111/pan.12163 }}</ref> The efficacy and safety of opioids in children have not been established.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cooper|first=Tess E.|last2=Fisher|first2=Emma|last3=Gray|first3=Andrew L.|last4=Krane|first4=Elliot|last5=Sethna|first5=Navil|last6=van Tilburg|first6=Miranda Al|last7=Zernikow|first7=Boris|last8=Wiffen|first8=Philip J.|date=Jul 2017|title=Opioids for chronic non-cancer pain in children and adolescents|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|volume=7|pages=CD012538|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD012538.pub2|issn=1469-493X|pmid=28745394}}</ref>
Other side effects of opioids are constipation, fatigue, and disorientation. Children can develop opioid tolerance, where larger doses are needed to have the same effect. Tolerance occurs earlier in children than in adults, especially with prolonged use.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Anand KJ, Willson DF, Berger J, Harrison R, Meert KL, Zimmerman J, Carcillo J, Newth CJ, Prodhan P, Dean JM, Nicholson C | title = Tolerance and withdrawal from prolonged opioid use in critically ill children | journal = Pediatrics | volume = 125 | issue = 5 | pages = e1208–25 | date = May 2010 | pmid = 20403936 | pmc = 3275643 | doi = 10.1542/peds.2009-0489 }}</ref> When tolerance to opioids develop, it takes a larger dose of the opioid to achieve the same analgesic effect.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cahill|first=Catherine M.|last2=Walwyn|first2=Wendy|last3=Taylor|first3=Anna M.W.|last4=Pradhan|first4=Amynah A.A.|last5=Evans|first5=Christopher J.|date=Nov 2016|title=Allostatic Mechanisms of Opioid Tolerance Beyond Desensitization and Downregulation|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5240843/|journal=Trends in Pharmacological Sciences|volume=37|issue=11|pages=963–976|doi=10.1016/j.tips.2016.08.002|issn=0165-6147|pmc=5240843|pmid=27670390|via=}}</ref> Non-pharmacological treatments have few side effects.{{mcn|date=November 2018}}
==Society and culture: Misconceptions== The [[Indication (medicine)|indication]]s that treatment is needed are not always clear for children because of poor assessments and the tendency to undertreat pain..
