{{Refimprove|date=August 2009}}

[[Image:Kulturbeutel1.jpg|thumb|right|A clear plastic toiletry bag]]
A '''toiletry bag''' (also called a '''toiletry kit''', '''ditty bag,''' '''doc kit''', '''bathroom kit''', '''sponge bag''', '''toilet bag''', '''toilet kit''', '''body hygiene kit''', '''travel kit''', '''wash bag''', or '''wet pack''') is a portable container—usually a pouch with a [[drawstring]] or zippered closure—which holds [[body hygiene]] and [[toiletry]] supplies such as [[toothbrush]] and [[toothpaste]], [[dental floss]], [[cotton swab]]s, [[deodorant]], [[nail clipper]]s, [[tweezers]], [[soap]], [[shaving]] supplies, [[hair brush]], [[tampon]]s, [[contact lens]]es and supplies, and similar items while travelling and in other circumstances where permanent shelves and cupboards are unavailable or impractical for use.

==Dopp kit==
''Dopp kit'' is a term particularly in use in the US for toiletry bags. The name derives from the early 20th century leather craftsman Charles Doppelt, whose company designed the case in 1926.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.americandialect.org/americandialectarchives/janxx98274.html |first= Jim | last= Rader |title= Etymology discussion | website= AmericanDialect.org |date=27 January 1998 |accessdate=27 January 2016 }}</ref>

Dopp kits became widely known during [[World War I]]<ref name= "about Buxton">{{cite web |url=http://buxton.co/pages/about-us |title=About Us | website= Buxton.co |accessdate=27 Jan 2016}}</ref> and [[World War II]]<ref name= AZ>{{Cite book|title = The A to Z Book of Menswear|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=MWeht2EeUWQC|publisher = The A to Z Book of Menswear|date = 2008-01-01|isbn = 9781897403259|language = en|first = Richard|last = Woolnough}}</ref> when they were issued to [[soldier]]s by the US military. The Dopp brand name was purchased by [[Samsonite]] in the early 1970s<ref name= AZ /> and was acquired by Buxton in 1979.<ref name= "about Buxton" />

The trademark ''Dopp'' was filed by Samsonite for registration at the US Trademark Office on March 24, 1980.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://tsdr.uspto.gov | title= Registration number 1193631 | website= uspto.gov | publisher= US Patent and Trademark Office |date= | accessdate= }}</ref> The class of goods for which it was applicable was “toilet cases sold empty, briefcases, briefcase type portfolios, sample and catalog cases sold empty, luggage identification tags, and traveling bags”. An additional filing for the trademark ''Dopp Kit'' was made on April 3, 1980 for the class of goods “travel kits, sold empty”.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://tsdr.uspto.gov/#caseNumber=73256578&caseType=SERIAL_NO&searchType=statusSearch|title=Trademark Application "DOPP KIT" (serial #73256578), Registration number 1197268 |publisher= United States Patent and Trademark Office | website= USPTO.gov |accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref> In both of those applications, Samsonite stated that the trademarks were first used in July 1936. The registration for ''Dopp Kit'' was cancelled in March 2003 when no one filed a required (Section 8) Declaration of Continued Use, but the required declarations have been filed for ''Dopp''. The marks were assigned to DHP Limited Partnership (dba Buxton) in 1990; the current owner of the ''Dopp'' trademark is listed as Buxton Acquisition Co., LLC, of [[Chicopee, Massachusetts|Chicopee]], [[Massachusetts]].{{cn|date=May 2015}}

